    <item>
      <title>Cosmological Principle</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/cosmological-principle/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/cosmological-principle/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The cosmological principle is the assumption that the universe, viewed on sufficiently large scales, is homogeneous (the same at every location) and isotropic (the same in every direction).&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;This is not obvious. At small scales the universe is spectacularly lumpy: stars, planets, galaxies, clusters, voids. But above roughly 300 megaparsecs (about a billion light-years), galaxy surveys show the distribution of matter becomes statistically uniform. The &lt;a href=&#34;../domains/structure/terms/cosmic-microwave-background.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;cosmic microwave background&lt;/a&gt; confirms isotropy to one part in 100,000.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Electromagnetic Spectrum</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/electromagnetic-spectrum/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/electromagnetic-spectrum/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The electromagnetic spectrum is the full range of electromagnetic radiation, from the longest radio waves to the shortest gamma rays. All electromagnetic radiation is the same physical phenomenon &amp;ndash; oscillating electric and magnetic fields propagating through space at the speed of &lt;a href=&#34;./light.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;light&lt;/a&gt; &amp;ndash; differing only in wavelength and frequency.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The spectrum, from longest to shortest wavelength:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;table&gt;&#xA;  &lt;thead&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;Band&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;Wavelength&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;          &lt;th&gt;Cosmological relevance&lt;/th&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/thead&gt;&#xA;  &lt;tbody&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Radio&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;&amp;gt; 1 mm&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Radio galaxies, pulsars, 21-cm hydrogen line&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Microwave&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;1 mm - 1 m&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;../domains/structure/terms/cosmic-microwave-background.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;Cosmic microwave background&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Infrared&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;700 nm - 1 mm&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;High-redshift galaxies, dust-obscured regions&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Visible&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;400 - 700 nm&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Optical galaxy surveys, supernovae&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Ultraviolet&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;10 - 400 nm&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Hot stars, active galactic nuclei&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;X-ray&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;0.01 - 10 nm&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Galaxy cluster gas, black hole accretion&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;      &lt;tr&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Gamma ray&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;&amp;lt; 0.01 nm&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;          &lt;td&gt;Gamma-ray bursts, extreme particle acceleration&lt;/td&gt;&#xA;      &lt;/tr&gt;&#xA;  &lt;/tbody&gt;&#xA;&lt;/table&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Wavelength &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\lambda&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and frequency &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;ν&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\nu&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; are related by &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;ν&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;c = \lambda \nu&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;. Shorter wavelength means higher frequency means higher energy per photon (&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;E&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;h&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;ν&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;E = h\nu&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;, where &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;h&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;h&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is Planck&amp;rsquo;s constant).&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>General Relativity</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/general-relativity/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/general-relativity/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;General relativity is Einstein&amp;rsquo;s theory of gravity (1915), in which the geometry of &lt;a href=&#34;./spacetime.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;spacetime&lt;/a&gt; is determined by the distribution of mass and energy, and the geometry of spacetime in turn determines how matter moves.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The Einstein field equations relate two mathematical objects: the Einstein tensor &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;G&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;μ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;ν&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;G_{\mu\nu}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (encoding spacetime curvature) and the stress-energy tensor &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;T&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;μ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;ν&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;T_{\mu\nu}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; (encoding the density and flow of mass-energy):&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34; display=&#34;block&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;G&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;μ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;ν&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;g&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;μ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;ν&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mfrac&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;8&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mi&gt;π&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;G&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;4&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;/mfrac&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;T&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;μ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;ν&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;G_{\mu\nu} + \Lambda g_{\mu\nu} = \frac{8\pi G}{c^4} T_{\mu\nu}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p&gt;The constant &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Lambda&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is the &lt;a href=&#34;../domains/structure/terms/dark-energy.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;cosmological constant&lt;/a&gt;, which Einstein originally introduced and later abandoned, and which was revived in 1998 when the &lt;a href=&#34;../domains/evolution/terms/accelerating-expansion.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;accelerating expansion&lt;/a&gt; was discovered.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Gravity</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/gravity/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/gravity/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Gravity is the phenomenon by which mass and energy determine the curvature of &lt;a href=&#34;./spacetime.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;spacetime&lt;/a&gt;, and curved spacetime determines the motion of matter.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Newton (1687) described gravity as a force between masses: proportional to the product of the masses, inversely proportional to the square of the distance. This predicts planetary orbits, tides, and projectile trajectories with extraordinary accuracy, and remains adequate for most terrestrial and solar-system calculations.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Einstein (1915) replaced Newton&amp;rsquo;s force with geometry. In &lt;a href=&#34;./general-relativity.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;general relativity&lt;/a&gt;, there is no gravitational force. Objects in free fall follow the straightest possible paths &amp;ndash; geodesics &amp;ndash; through curved spacetime. What we perceive as gravitational attraction is the convergence of geodesics near massive bodies. Mass tells spacetime how to curve; curved spacetime tells matter how to move.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Lambda-CDM Model</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/lambda-cdm-model/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/lambda-cdm-model/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The Lambda-CDM model is the standard model of cosmology. It describes a universe that is spatially flat, governed by &lt;a href=&#34;./general-relativity.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;general relativity&lt;/a&gt;, and composed of approximately 5% &lt;a href=&#34;../domains/structure/terms/baryonic-matter.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;baryonic matter&lt;/a&gt;, 27% cold &lt;a href=&#34;../domains/structure/terms/dark-matter.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;dark matter&lt;/a&gt; (CDM), and 68% &lt;a href=&#34;../domains/structure/terms/dark-energy.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;dark energy&lt;/a&gt; in the form of a cosmological constant (Lambda, &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Lambda&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;).&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The model has six free parameters:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;ol&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Ω&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;b&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mi&gt;h&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Omega_b h^2&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; baryon density&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi mathvariant=&#34;normal&#34;&gt;Ω&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;msup&gt;&lt;mi&gt;h&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mn&gt;2&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/msup&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\Omega_c h^2&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; cold dark matter density&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;θ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;∗&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\theta_*&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; angular size of the sound horizon at &lt;a href=&#34;../domains/evolution/terms/recombination.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;recombination&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;τ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\tau&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; optical depth to reionization&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;n&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;s&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;n_s&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; scalar spectral index (tilt of the primordial fluctuation spectrum)&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;A&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mi&gt;s&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;A_s&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt; &amp;ndash; amplitude of primordial fluctuations&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ol&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;These six numbers, combined with the &lt;a href=&#34;../domains/evolution/terms/friedmann-equations.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;Friedmann equations&lt;/a&gt; and the physics of the pre-recombination plasma, predict the angular power spectrum of the &lt;a href=&#34;../domains/structure/terms/cosmic-microwave-background.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;cosmic microwave background&lt;/a&gt;, the distribution of &lt;a href=&#34;../domains/structure/terms/galaxy.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;galaxies&lt;/a&gt;, the abundances of light elements, the expansion history, and the age of the universe. The predictions match observations across all these independent tests.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Light</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/light/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/light/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Light is electromagnetic radiation: oscillating electric and magnetic fields that propagate through space at a fixed speed, approximately 300,000 kilometers per second in vacuum. This speed &amp;ndash; denoted &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;c&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;c&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &amp;ndash; is the fastest that any signal, particle, or information can travel.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Light is the primary messenger of cosmology. Nearly everything we know about the universe beyond our solar system arrives as electromagnetic radiation collected by telescopes. Because light travels at finite speed, observing a distant object means observing it as it was when the light left it. A galaxy ten billion light-years away is seen as it was ten billion years ago. Looking far away is looking back in time.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Redshift</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/redshift/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/redshift/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Redshift is the stretching of &lt;a href=&#34;./light.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;light&lt;/a&gt; to longer wavelengths. In cosmology, the dominant cause is the expansion of space itself: as &lt;a href=&#34;./light.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;light&lt;/a&gt; travels through an expanding universe, the space it traverses stretches, and the light&amp;rsquo;s wavelength stretches with it. Longer wavelength means redder, hence &amp;ldquo;redshift.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The redshift &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;z&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;z&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; of a source is defined by:&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34; display=&#34;block&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;mo&gt;+&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mi&gt;z&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mfrac&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt;observed&lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt;emitted&lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mfrac&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mfrac&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt;now&lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt;emit&lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mfrac&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mfrac&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;msub&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mtext&gt;emit&lt;/mtext&gt;&lt;/msub&gt;&lt;/mfrac&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;1 + z = \frac{\lambda_{\text{observed}}}{\lambda_{\text{emitted}}} = \frac{a_{\text{now}}}{a_{\text{emit}}} = \frac{1}{a_{\text{emit}}}&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p&gt;where &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;λ&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;\lambda&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is wavelength and &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;a&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;a&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is the &lt;a href=&#34;../domains/evolution/terms/scale-factor.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;scale factor&lt;/a&gt;. A galaxy at &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;z&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;=&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;z = 1&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt; emitted its light when the universe was half its current size. The &lt;a href=&#34;../domains/structure/terms/cosmic-microwave-background.md&#34; class=&#34;link-internal&#34;&gt;cosmic microwave background&lt;/a&gt; has &lt;span class=&#34;katex&#34;&gt;&lt;math xmlns=&#34;http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML&#34;&gt;&lt;semantics&gt;&lt;mrow&gt;&lt;mi&gt;z&lt;/mi&gt;&lt;mo&gt;≈&lt;/mo&gt;&lt;mn&gt;1100&lt;/mn&gt;&lt;/mrow&gt;&lt;annotation encoding=&#34;application/x-tex&#34;&gt;z \approx 1100&lt;/annotation&gt;&lt;/semantics&gt;&lt;/math&gt;&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Spacetime</title>
      <link>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/spacetime/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://emsenn.net/library/domains/science/domains/cosmology/terms/spacetime/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Spacetime is the four-dimensional continuum combining three spatial dimensions and one time dimension, in which all physical events occur. Special relativity (Einstein, 1905) demonstrated that space and time are not independent: the measured distance and duration between two events depend on the observer&amp;rsquo;s state of motion, but the spacetime interval between them does not. This interval &amp;ndash; roughly, the difference between squared time separation and squared spatial separation &amp;ndash; is the invariant quantity that all observers agree on.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
